{% doc %}
  @prompt
    The company's founder defended the price by making a direct comparison to established brands, arguing that the use of superior materials (acetate versus the injected plastic used in some lower-priced Ray-Ban models) and the inclusion of polarised lenses as standard means a comparably equipped product from a legacy brand would cost significantly more, in the range of £170 to over £200.4
    This justification, while logical from a product development standpoint, highlights a dangerous disconnect. New Vantage Co. defines its value internally based on a bill of materials and features relative to legacy luxury brands. The target consumer, however, perceives value relative to a vast spectrum of readily available online alternatives. This includes glasses from £6 at SelectSpecs, frequent "2 for 1" deals from market leader Glasses Direct, and functionally adequate products from brands like Goodr.4 The founder's argument requires a level of consumer education on material science that is not widespread. Most shoppers cannot visually differentiate between acetate and injected plastic and are primarily guided by price, brand recognition, and style. Therefore, the brand's marketing cannot simply state "high quality"; it must actively and compellingly demonstrate it. Without a concerted effort to make the invisible value of superior materials and craftsmanship tangible, the brand risks being perceived as simply overpriced.
    , align the colors and  129 brand price including polarised lenses or prescription lenses with bluelight or 1.6 index based on prescriptions also make sure it fully customizable and mobile friendly 
{% enddoc %}
